metadata.name: Dithered Nostalgia #193
metadata.description:
Have you ever struck by a sudden surge of nostalgia?
Making you stop everything you did at that moment,
Trying hard to remember the memory behind it, and failed to do so?

Each of these lands hold a nostalgia unlocked,
Like how good nostalgia are, it’s dithered and full of holes.
Holes that can be filled with your own memories and interpretations.

• • •

The second collaboration of MEK.txt and IceRain in FXHash. This time using MEK.txt’s landscape pixelart series and its distinctive dithering textures, brilliantly translated into code by IceRain to pixel-perfect iterations.

Dithered Nostalgia is a step up from MEK.txt & IceRain’s first project (Bento Boxes), trying to make more sophisticated, more detailed and challenging things based on something they passionate about; landscape.

Controls:
[1] Set the resolution to Medium Resolution
[2] Set the resolution to High Resolution

metadata.name: NESTED IDENTITIES #116
metadata.description:
Nested identities redact fingerprints but deeper meaning can still be found.

Nested identifies refers to the idea that a person may have multiple identities that are interconnected and interdependent. These identities may be related to a person's cultural background, ethnicity, nationality, gender, sexual orientation, social class, profession, and other factors. It is possible that a person may want to conceal or redact certain aspects of their identity in order to protect their privacy or to avoid discrimination or persecution. However, even if certain details about a person's identity are hidden or redacted, it may still be possible to infer deeper meaning or understand more about their experiences and perspectives based on the context in which they express themselves and the information that is available.


The concept of nested identities highlights the complexity and multifaceted nature of a person's identity, and how different aspects of identity can intersect and influence each other. It is important to recognize and respect the diversity of identities that people may hold, and to be mindful of the ways in which power dynamics and social context can shape how people present and express their identities. It is also important to recognize that people's identities may evolve and change over time, and that everyone has the right to self-identify and to define their own identity on their own terms.

Press p to download a high quality export.

metadata.name: Tree Skyness #66
metadata.description:
Tree Skyness

Crown shyness occurs when the tops of fully grown trees avoid touching each other, forming gaps in the canopy. This piece simulates that phenomena and plays with celestial object avoidance. Features include four seasons, time of day, up to 12 trees, and many special options. HD rendering can be enabled for 8192x8192 resolution. 10% of primary sales will be donated to the fxhash Ukraine fund.

Click to randomize with the same settings.

By Frank Force @KilledByAPixel
Made with Vanilla JavaScript

Controls
1 = Save a 2048x2048 png (or right click save)
2 = Toggle HD (may not work in some environments)
3 = Toggle noise (disable for clearer image)

metadata.name: DOS DELIGHT: DITHER #62
metadata.description:
As a child who encountered computers in the nostalgic era of the 90s, 'Dos Delight' stands as one of my most intimate generative art projects, bridging the gap between my early childhood and vivid memories intertwined with the world of computing.

In this generative art, I aim to recreate the aesthetics of 90s computers, tapping into the nostalgia of a bygone era. The algorithm, inspired by the playfulness of childhood, generates whimsical, childlike paintings reminiscent of a time when computers were new, and learning happened through wild exploration.

Crafted to capture the boundless creativity of a child lost in play, the algorithm yields artworks adorned with pixelated allure, employing a captivating blend of black and white enhanced by dither aesthetics.

Press 4 or 8 to export in 4k and 8k in PNG.
Press 's' to export in screen resolution.

Murat Atimtay 2024 | @atimtay | https://www.atimtay.xyz"

metadata.name: NOT A DOS DELIGHT #59
metadata.description:
"NOT A DOS DELIGHT" continues the legacy of the DOS DELIGHT series but with a modern twist, marked by the use of GPUs to create an illusion of Turkish paper marbling within the framework of retro computer aesthetics. This project designed to adapt to multiple aspect ratios; while maintaining determinism in features like color palettes and glyphs, it introduces subtle variations based on aspect ratio, ensuring a unique visual experience for each device.

Additionally, this project incorporates a fresh set of color palettes, distinct from the DOS DELIGHT series, drawing inspiration from the earthy hues found in Turkish marbling pigments.



Press 1 or 2 to export PNG.

For the optimal experience, I highly recommend engaging with "NOT A DOS DELIGHT" in fullscreen mode.

Murat Atimtay 2024 | @atimtay | www.atimtay.xyz

metadata.description:
🌘🌗🌖Shattered Moons🌔🌓🌒

Explore deep space moons through this pure SVG generative experiment.

Features:
- Striped Background
- Shadows
- Vapors
- Horizontal Vapors
- Meteors
- Colored Meteors
- White Moon (0.5%)

SVG being a vectorial format, this work can be displayed/printed at any size.
Press 's' on Live View to save the SVG.
Press 'p' on Live View using a Chromium based browser to export as PNG.

Also, to fully enjoy your piece, I'd suggest to use a Chromium based browser as the SVG renderer gives more details.

metadata.name: Agharta #194
metadata.description:
It may appear as an indecipherable map to some. To others, it may present itself as a cross section of an underground cave. Or maybe an uncanny landscape of volcanic activity, a diagram of geological strata, or even something else entirely. Some vague structure may also appear; is it the remains of an ancient civilization? Or perhaps a glimpse into our own tomorrow?

In "Agharta", I sought to create a generative work that could invite the viewer to explore the depths of their imagination and uncover hidden structures within the seemingly chaotic composition. The idea came to me when I was exploring Simplex noise and pixel displacement in Cables. I was surprised by the emergent structures that appeared when some set of parameters paired with the right texture. 

The title of the piece references the mythical underground world said to be located at the earth's core. This idea of hidden depths and secret worlds within the earth resonates with the abstract and enigmatic nature of the result generated by the noise. Imagery of landscape, vague structures, or geological features may appear but never stand out on its own; it exists in a state of constant flow and intersection as if viewed from another dimension. And just like the myth itself that bring up numerous theories that doesn’t necessarily connected to each other, it hints at that idea of an elusive imagined realm while never actually represent it completely.



=========

Controls:

[1] Set resolution to 716 x 1024px (default)

[2] Set resolution to 1433 x 2048px

[3] Set resolution to 2688 x 3840px

* The presets above are suitable for screen viewing up to 4k screen resolution. To set a custom resolution for printing and other purpose, add &res=[desired resolution] at the end of the URL. It will set the height of the image, and the width will be calculated automatically at 0.7 ratio. For example to get a resolution of 4911 x 7016px (about the size of A2 paper), add &res=7016 as URL parameter.

[Scroll/pinch] to zoom and drag to pan

[r] or [zoom out to max] Reset position

[c] Capture a screenshot of the current state at rendered resolution


Notes:

* This project use shaders that relies on GPU. Hi-res output may slow down your device. Since it also utilize GPU instance for thumbnail rendering, expect longer time for every iterations to be signed by fx(hash).

* If 'glitching' occurs or the composition behaves differently at different resolution, just refresh the page to reset it (except for the thin lines, which are always drawn at approximately 1 pixel, so expect it to vary at different resolution).

Made with cables.gl, a node-based webgl environment

XALTED 2022

metadata.name: Faux #154
metadata.description:
This project is borne out of my longstanding fascination with brushwork, and the intricate textures that can be created with a brush, some paint and a canvas. Brush strokes are simulated using many overlapping lines and given texture and depth using a custom shader. Another important aspect of this work, is the composite forms that are created by the brush strokes, which are my attempt to emulate the emphatic energy of many abstract painters that have come before me. Color palettes are named after common paint colors, based on the background color used for the palette.

Those who collect during the first tier of the Dutch Auction can claim a signed print. They will be printed on A3 Hahnemuhle Photo Rag, and shipped to the collector free of charge. More details on how to claim a print and specify the necessary shipping information will be provided via the artists twitter (@landlinesart1).

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.
